results.notes:
NJMA foray collections made by several participants.
We always find these birch-associated scaber stalks from sect. Scabra in Stokes and other places in far northern NJ during summer and early fall. Sequencing (ITS) revealed that in addition to what is presumed to be L. snellii (e.g., obs 329898 & possibly obs 288473) there is another very common taxon possessing essentially the same ITS2 sequence as snellii but a very different ITS1 sequence (e.g., obs 281644, obs 288622, obs 330112, and obs 370555). It is very likely that the latter entity is a published species, possibly L. flavostipitatum (?). Since ITS1 is suitable strictly for barcoding in Leccinum and the more conserved ITS2 sublocus is of some basic phylogenetic value for this genus (for grouping species into clades/subclades), I lumped these two taxa into the “snellii group”.
My experience with these summer birch boletes led me to tentatively separating them on the basis of cap morphologies. Snellii has a darker cap with large patches of much lighter, almost whitish, color, whereas the other species has a lighter brown cap covered with darker appressed fibrils. As for the staining of the exposed flesh, both species stain both blue and red, mostly when fresh and well-hydrated (e.g., obs 329898 & obs 370555). When the flesh is more dry, the onset of colors is delayed and the staining is more erratic and less intense. In “cf. flavostipitatum”, oxidative bluing is often restricted to the very bottom of the stipe, while the upper stipe and cap either don’t redden at all or barely turn reddish-brown.
As far as the present collections of 7 fruitbodies is concerned, its is possible it’s a mixture of both snellii and “cf. flavostipitatum”. These would have to be individually sequenced.
Five (5) basidiomata were preserved and were two discarded (see notes in the images).
